1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,080
INSTRUCTOR: Now,
let's look at what

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:04,520
happens on observational
cohorts when

3
00:00:04,520 --> 00:00:08,600
we try to recover
the treatment effect.

4
00:00:08,600 --> 00:00:11,040
We attempt to recover
the hazard ratio

5
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:14,240
as reported in prior
clinical trials

6
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:16,560
of the respective therapies.

7
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:20,160
The dashed red
line in each figure

8
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:23,280
is the trial benchmark
for that setting.

9
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:28,080
The bars show four estimators
on the same real-world data--

10
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:33,720
the original naive estimate, a
multivariable Cox adjustment,

11
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:38,360
prognostic matching, the
first step only of road one,

12
00:00:38,360 --> 00:00:41,680
and the full road
three pipeline.

13
00:00:41,680 --> 00:00:45,820
On the left, we can
see the GIST data

14
00:00:45,820 --> 00:00:49,280
set, which contains patient.

15
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:51,680
And for these patients,
we need to decide

16
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:55,120
whether we are going to
prescribe imatinib or just

17
00:00:55,120 --> 00:00:56,760
observation.

18
00:00:56,760 --> 00:01:01,380
In GIST, the RCT, the randomized
clinical trial benchmark,

19
00:01:01,380 --> 00:01:05,290
is around a hazard
ratio of 0.46.

20
00:01:05,290 --> 00:01:08,210
Starting from the raw
cohort, the original estimate

21
00:01:08,210 --> 00:01:09,750
is badly distorted.

22
00:01:09,750 --> 00:01:13,970
It is well above 2, which is
definitely the wrong direction.

23
00:01:13,970 --> 00:01:17,450
Simply adding covariates
in multivariable analysis

24
00:01:17,450 --> 00:01:20,610
pulls the estimate down,
and prognostic matching

25
00:01:20,610 --> 00:01:21,850
helps a bit more.

26
00:01:21,850 --> 00:01:25,610
But neither reaches
the trial target.

27
00:01:25,610 --> 00:01:28,930
After we add road three's
latent burden balancing

28
00:01:28,930 --> 00:01:32,130
on top of the prognostic
match, the hazard ratio

29
00:01:32,130 --> 00:01:35,810
aligns with the trial right
around the dashed line.

30
00:01:35,810 --> 00:01:40,230
In GIST, key prognostic features
like size, mitotic count,

31
00:01:40,230 --> 00:01:43,210
and tumor site carry
a lot of signal.

32
00:01:43,210 --> 00:01:46,290
So once we control observed
prognoses and balance

33
00:01:46,290 --> 00:01:50,490
the residual latent burden, the
cohort behaves as if randomized,

34
00:01:50,490 --> 00:01:53,050
and we recover the
trial-like effect.

35
00:01:53,050 --> 00:01:57,610
In the right figure, you can
see results on the RPS cohort.

36
00:01:57,610 --> 00:02:02,770
The RPS cohort contains patients
with retroperitoneal sarcoma.

37
00:02:02,770 --> 00:02:06,610
And we want to either prescribe
preoperative radiotherapy

38
00:02:06,610 --> 00:02:08,229
or not.

39
00:02:08,229 --> 00:02:12,990
For this cohort, the dashed
line, the ground truth,

40
00:02:12,990 --> 00:02:15,590
is around 0.75.

41
00:02:15,590 --> 00:02:18,890
The original observational
estimate is far from that,

42
00:02:18,890 --> 00:02:21,770
and multivariable
analysis doesn't fix it.

43
00:02:21,770 --> 00:02:24,390
They both remain too
optimistic about the effect

44
00:02:24,390 --> 00:02:26,070
of radiotherapy.

45
00:02:26,070 --> 00:02:28,930
Prognostic matching
improves the estimate.

46
00:02:28,930 --> 00:02:30,930
We move towards the dashed line.

47
00:02:30,930 --> 00:02:32,830
But there is still a gap.

48
00:02:32,830 --> 00:02:36,870
With road three, once we balance
the latent unobserved factor

49
00:02:36,870 --> 00:02:40,710
across arms, the estimate
lands near the benchmark,

50
00:02:40,710 --> 00:02:43,070
and the error bars tighten.

51
00:02:43,070 --> 00:02:45,710
An interesting observation
is that our method

52
00:02:45,710 --> 00:02:48,190
correct the treatment
effect estimation

53
00:02:48,190 --> 00:02:52,630
in both and over and
underestimation scenario,

54
00:02:52,630 --> 00:02:55,110
left and right.

55
00:02:55,110 --> 00:02:58,070
Now, in the next set
of results we have,

56
00:02:58,070 --> 00:03:02,870
we start from RCTs, where we
know the true hazard ratio.

57
00:03:02,870 --> 00:03:04,930
These cohorts are balanced.

58
00:03:04,930 --> 00:03:08,770
So in order to make them more
observation-like cohorts,

59
00:03:08,770 --> 00:03:13,480
we intentionally inject bias
to mimic the real world.

60
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:15,880
We do this by
randomly resampling

61
00:03:15,880 --> 00:03:20,640
patients with bad outcomes and
adding them back in the cohort.

62
00:03:20,640 --> 00:03:23,960
That basically inflates
poor outcomes in a way

63
00:03:23,960 --> 00:03:26,300
that correlates with
treatment assignment,

64
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:31,760
creating selection bias, like in
observational real-life cohorts.

65
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:35,580
The dashed red line marks
the true trial hazard ratio

66
00:03:35,580 --> 00:03:39,040
before we inject bias, and
this is the hazard ratio

67
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:41,720
we want to recover
after the road three

68
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:44,560
pipeline is implemented.

69
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:47,720
So focusing on the
left, we have STRASS.

70
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:50,880
STRASS is a randomized
clinical trial

71
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:55,340
that was conducted on
patients with, again,

72
00:03:55,340 --> 00:03:59,160
primary retroperitoneal
sarcomas, again, regarding

73
00:03:59,160 --> 00:04:01,800
preoperative radiotherapy.

74
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:07,760
After injecting confounding, the
original estimate jumps above 1.

75
00:04:07,760 --> 00:04:11,440
Multivariable adjustment
helps but still overshoots.

76
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:15,290
Prognostic matching gets
closer but not on target.

77
00:04:15,290 --> 00:04:19,470
With road three, after balancing
the latent unobserved burden,

78
00:04:19,470 --> 00:04:23,090
the estimate returns
to approximately 1,

79
00:04:23,090 --> 00:04:26,010
and the error bars
tighten again.

80
00:04:26,010 --> 00:04:29,610
Now, on the right, we
have the BRT cohort.

81
00:04:29,610 --> 00:04:33,490
This data set contains patients
with extremity sarcomas.

82
00:04:33,490 --> 00:04:39,090
The question here is also should
they get radiotherapy or not.

83
00:04:39,090 --> 00:04:42,810
The injected bias pushes
original and multivariable

84
00:04:42,810 --> 00:04:46,890
analysis toward 1, toward
basically no effect.

85
00:04:46,890 --> 00:04:51,050
Prognostic matching partially
correct the treatment effect.

86
00:04:51,050 --> 00:04:55,810
However, it is road three that
actually pulls the estimate down

87
00:04:55,810 --> 00:05:00,490
to approximately 0.5,
recovering the protective signal

88
00:05:00,490 --> 00:05:02,490
of the therapy.

89
00:05:02,490 --> 00:05:06,250
A small gap remains because
for this specific data set,

90
00:05:06,250 --> 00:05:08,930
we have a smaller
effective sample.

91
00:05:08,930 --> 00:05:14,890
But our result is much closer
to truth than the alternatives.

92
00:05:14,890 --> 00:05:18,610
To summarize, road three
builds on road one's

93
00:05:18,610 --> 00:05:21,790
prognostic matching by
adding a principled way

94
00:05:21,790 --> 00:05:26,190
to quantify and balance
unobserved prognostic factors

95
00:05:26,190 --> 00:05:30,790
in observational survival data
without requiring a target

96
00:05:30,790 --> 00:05:33,030
randomized clinical trial.

97
00:05:33,030 --> 00:05:35,270
After balancing
this latent factor

98
00:05:35,270 --> 00:05:38,030
and refitting a
multivariable Cox model,

99
00:05:38,030 --> 00:05:41,270
we obtain hazard
ratio estimates that

100
00:05:41,270 --> 00:05:44,150
are trial-like on
real-world cohorts

101
00:05:44,150 --> 00:05:46,770
and stable under
strong stress tests,

102
00:05:46,770 --> 00:05:50,310
as we did with randomized
clinical trial cohorts, where,

103
00:05:50,310 --> 00:05:54,630
as we said, we injected
artificial confounding.

104
00:05:54,630 --> 00:05:58,550
This is a practical path to
credible effect estimation

105
00:05:58,550 --> 00:06:02,070
and actionable precision
medicine in settings where

106
00:06:02,070 --> 00:06:06,230
trials are absent or
incomplete, since one can now

107
00:06:06,230 --> 00:06:11,550
use the RCT-like cohort created
through the road three pipeline

108
00:06:11,550 --> 00:06:14,310
train, for example,
optimal policy trees

109
00:06:14,310 --> 00:06:17,790
to get specific policies or
treatment recommendations

110
00:06:17,790 --> 00:06:20,270
for each cohort subset.

111
00:06:20,270 --> 00:06:21,870
Thank you for
listening, and good luck

112
00:06:21,870 --> 00:06:24,140
with the rest of the modules.